<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Ofsted Annual Report 2012-13: Commons Education Committee inquiry</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">OAR0017</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Newham College</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.97pt; padding-left:5.03pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">Newham College is one of the country’s </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">largest further education c</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">olleges. With two campuses and five learning centres in East London, and a range of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">high-quality provision from pre-entry to postgraduate, it serves some 20,000 students a year in one of the UK’s most deprived boroughs. As well as its core provision – ranging from engineering to English, science to sport, hairdressing to hospitality – the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> College runs a number of subsidiary businesses and charities, including Bermondsey’s Fashion &amp; Textile Museum and the Le</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">arning Revolution Trust. Alongside</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> its high-performing curriculum teams, the College is noted for its innovative approach in various fi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">elds, not least public policy, where it is the only college with a dedicated team.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.97pt; padding-left:5.03pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">This submission is made by the College in the hope that the Committee might continue its </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">specific </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">scrutiny of Ofsted’s further education role, as begun in last year’s sessi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">on (in which we delighted to find the College’s evidence proved useful). Our comments refer to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">the FE &amp; skills sub-report only, and we have drafted questions which we </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">hope</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> the Committee might find useful in its session.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">Uncited</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> quotations are from the annu</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">al report (2012-13).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; text-decoration:underline">Cause for optimism</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; text-decoration:underline">; Ofsted’s capability</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.97pt; padding-left:5.03pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">We are pleased to read that, following a further year of inspections, Ofsted is more optimistic about the quality of FE, and the sector’s capacity to improve. Those of us in the sector are well</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> aware of its capabilities, and we would urge Ofsted to reflect on the considerable change the sector has been subject to, and has needed to respond to, over the past few years. This in itself takes some time to settle down, and we therefore believe that a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">s these changes embed further, the truer picture of the sector’s performance will emerge – as it is clearly beginning to do.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.97pt; padding-left:5.03pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">We would further urge Ofsted to continue strengthening its own knowledge of FE, and in particular the number of staff with relevan</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">t experience. The Commons Education Committee has noted previously that Ofsted’s structure – from Board to inspector level – does not have enough relevant experience</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> We are pleased that Ofsted’s in-house FE knowledge has improved since the last annual re</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">port; the truer picture painted this year may owe something to that.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Does Ofsted believe it now has the in-house capability and capacity to understand that FE sector as fully as it should</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold"> (and as it does the schools sector)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Does Ofsted acknowledge that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">the FE sector has been subject to great change, which takes time to settle into? Does Ofsted believe that – either alone, or working with the new Commissioner – it could do more to support and challenge the sector in a productive way?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.97pt; padding-left:5.03pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">Ofsted’s report come</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">s at a time when, yet again, FE is suffering a funding cut disproportionate to those in other parts of the education sector. In particular, FE receives comparatively little support given the deprivation of many of its students (around three-quarters in our</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> case).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Does Ofsted support the development of a ‘learner </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">premium’ </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">to support students who have been eligible for the pupil premium to ensure that young people from disadvantaged backgrounds achieve in FE?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; text-decoration:underline">Preparation for employment</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; text-decoration:underline">; English and maths</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.97pt; padding-left:5.03pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">It is good to see Ofsted’s recognition of one of FE’s core purposes: preparing people for work. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">We agree with Ofsted that – particularly as more pre-16s are recruited directly to FE colleges – the passing of information from schools will need to become les</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">s “burdensome and bureaucratic”. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Has Ofsted raised the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">“</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">burdensome and bureaucratic</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold"> passing of information between schools and colleges with the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">? What can it do to support colleges on this issue?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.97pt; padding-left:5.03pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">Whilst the annual report is critical of English and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">maths success rates in many colleges, it does acknowledge that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">these are better when taught as functional skills than through GCSE. At present, however, the recruitment of teachers skilled in both vocational fields and literacy &amp; numeracy can present a cha</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">llenge. Other countries have acknowledged that, in part, this is about training needs, including ongoing development for staff.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">D</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">oes Ofsted support calls by the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold"> Committee</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold"> and others for improved CPD and training for teachers, including critically those in FE? Does Ofsted believe this would improve the rates of success in English and maths amongst FE students?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; text-decoration:underline">Labour market intelligence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.97pt; padding-left:5.03pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">We agree with Ofsted that colleges </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">do not have a strong enough understanding of their local labour market needs; improving this is critical in ensuring that FE can deliver the skills and training which employers really want. At Newham College we have taken a number of innovative steps in th</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">is arena, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">including the development of a Skills &amp; Employment Board of local industry representatives, and commissioning a large piece of research forecasting East London business and employment growth over the coming years. We would urge other colleges to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">pursue such mechanisms, and would ask that Ofsted consider how it could support this – for example through publication of a ‘best practice’ guide in this area.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.97pt; padding-left:5.03pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">Ofsted itself has access to a national data-set on colleges’ provision and student destination </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">data which no college alone can replicate. Whilst LEPs and other </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">fora</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> can assist in this, we would encourage Ofsted to consider how best it can share that data with other colleges, the better to enable the growth of relevant provision.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> That said, colleges </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">need to be centrally involved in LEPs and in local growth strategies, which is not fully appreciated in some areas. At the same time, employers are still not fully involved in these arenas either. This local joint planning is particularly important for stu</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">dents with SEN and disabilities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Could Ofsted find means to support colleges’ understanding of the labour market and its needs, for example by publishing a ‘best practice’ guide examining colleges making impressive steps in this area?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Could Ofsted </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">consider a similar guide on local planning in this area, its importance, and examples of good practice, to encourage LEPs in other areas to replicate?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">The inspection framework for FE argues for an understanding of (and delivery to) the ‘local’ area, which</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> is positive, but we share concerns that Ofsted lacks full appreciation of the meaning of ‘local’ in an FE context. A college with 20,000 learners will inevitably serve a wider catchment area than a school.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Can Ofsted confirm what it looks for in judging </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">colleges’ ‘local’ delivery and knowledge?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; text-decoration:underline">Apprenticeships</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; text-decoration:underline">; careers guidance</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">As the Committee Chair noted following his own visit to Newham College (as reported in the Standard), the role of colleges is not well-publicised pre-16, as there is a disincenti</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">ve for schools to advise pupils down the “FE path” (given per-pupil funding arrangements), combined with a “scarily high” level “of ignorance” concerning colleges’ real work and roles.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> Alongside this, careers guidance – which has suffered painful damage o</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">ver the past two years – does not focus strongly enough on Apprenticeships </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">or vocational education as </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">viable path</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt"> (despite politicians’ rhetoric). This is shown in the statistics quoted in the annual report, which show a slight numerical growth in pre-19 </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">Apprenticeships, but a significant drop as a percentage of all Apprenticeship starts.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Does Ofsted believe that more should be done, by Government or other avenues, to improve young people’s knowledge of Apprenticeships as a viable pathway?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Does Ofsted sh</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">are the concerns of the Committee Chair that teachers and schools are reluctant to advise young people into FE, even when that path is right for them? What can be done to improve that situation?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">The role and performance of Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">: second report of the Education Committee, Session 2010-12, esp. paragraphs 66-69, and chap</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">ter 4</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> See </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Great Teachers: attracting, training and retaining the best</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">, ninth report of the Education Committee, Session 2010-12</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.standard.co.uk/news/education/pupils-not-told-about-vocational-college-courses-8885889.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://w</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">ww.standard.co.uk/news/education/pupils-not-told-about-vocational-college-courses-8885889.html</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p></body></html>